{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01AzymMe4j359UJXd3MnA3zv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for this AI-powered code generation service. I need to determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures for each behavior.\n\nThe service workflow is:\n1. Accept natural language description\n2. Generate implementation using LLM\n3. Run generated code against test suite\n4. Iteratively refine if tests fail (max 3 attempts)\n5. Return result\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 1: Generated function signature matches expected interface\n\n**Description**: The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.\n\n**Analysis**:\n- This checks if the LLM generates code with the correct signature\n- The signature comparison itself is deterministic (string/AST comparison)\n- BUT correctness depends on what the LLM actually generates\n- A mock LLM could always return \"def foo(a: int) -> int: return a\" and the test would pass\n- A real LLM might generate \"def foo(x: int) -> int: return x\" or the wrong signature\n- The failure boundary: whether the real LLM interprets the description correctly and generates matching signature\n\n**Real failure**: A real LLM generates a signature that doesn't match the expected interface (different parameter names, missing types, wrong return type). A mock would always return the \"correct\" signature.\n\n**Level considerations**:\n- Mock-miss: YES - a mock could always return the right signature, missing real LLM failures to interpret\n- Real-infra: The signature parsing/validation is local, but the signature generation depends on LLM\n- LLM-dep: YES - whether a real LLM generates the right signature is non-deterministic. Different models, prompts, or temperatures might generate different signatures\n\nThis